1.2 grammar of graphics: geoms

  1. For a line chart: geom_line()
    For a boxplot: geom_boxplot()
    For a histogram: geom_histogram()
    For an area chart: geom_area()

2.These two graphs wont look different.
Because in the first command, the geom_point() and geom_smooth() both inherited the arguments of ggplot()(data=mpg,mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)), which are exactly the same as the ones in the geom_point() and geom_smooth() of the second command.

#graph 1
ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) +geom_point() +geom_smooth()
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

#graph 2
ggplot() +geom_point(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) +geom_smooth(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy))
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

  1. The se argument controls the display of confidence interval around the smooth line.
    The default value passed to se is TRUE.

  2. To make the graph:

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = displ, y = cty)) +geom_point(aes(color=drv)) +geom_smooth(se=FALSE)
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

1.2.1 grammar of graphics: Statistical transformations

  1. The geom_col() makes bar charts. It makes the heights of the bars to represent values in the data.
    Difference between geom_bar() and geom_col(): geom_bar makes the height of the bar proportional to the number of cases in each group (or if the weight aesthetic is supplied, the sum of the weights) while geom_col() makes the heights of the bars to represent values in the data.
    geom_bar uses stat_count by default and counts the number of cases at each x position while geom_col uses stat_identity and leaves the data as it is.

  2. To make the same graph:

#Graph 1 (using geom)
ggplot(data=mpg, aes(x=hwy)) + geom_bar()

#Graph 2 (using stat)
ggplot(data=mpg, aes(x=hwy)) + stat_count()

  1. The 4 variables that are computed by stat_smooth() are y(predicted value), ymin(lower pointwise confidence interval around the mean), ymax(upper pointwise confidence interval around the mean) and se(standard error).
    y is displayed as the points on the predicted line. ymin and ymax are displayed respectively as the lower and upper boundary of the shaded area around the predicted line. The vertical width of the shaded area is proportional to se.
    There are many parameters that can control the behavior of stat_smooth().For example, the smoothing method is controlled by method, whether to display the confidence interval is controlled by se, whether the fit spans the full range of the plot or just the data is controlled by span and the level of confidence interval is controlled by level.

  2. Five pairs:
    (1)geom_boxplot() and stat_boxplot()
    (2)geom_smooth() and stat_smooth()
    (3)geom_contour() and stat_contour()
    (4)geom_density() and stat_density()
    (5)geom_quantile() and stat_quantile()
    Some geoms and stats go together because the data is kept as it is in these cases.
    stat_count is an exception to the rule because stat_count uses the number of cases at each x position rather than the value of x.

  3. We need to set group = 1 because if we dont, the proportions of the bars will all have a value of 1 like the following two graphs.If we dont set group = 1, ggplot will use the counts of each subset of cut as denominator rather than the counts of the whole dataset to determine their proportions.

#Graph 1
ggplot(data = diamonds) + geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = cut, y = ..prop..)) 

#Graph 2
ggplot(data = diamonds) + geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = cut, fill = color, y = ..prop..))

  1. It solved the problem. Because group = 1 leads to that there is only one group in the graph so there is only one kind of color displayed in the graph.
#Graph 1 
ggplot(data = diamonds) + geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = cut, group = 1,fill = color, y = ..prop..))

#Graph 2
ggplot(data = diamonds) + geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = cut, group = color,fill = color, y = ..prop..))

1.3 grammar of graphics: Positional adjustments

  1. The problem is that there are many data points overlapping thus we cannot know the density of data points from this graph.
    We can improve it by using geom_jitter() or geom_count() or alpha.
ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = cty, y = hwy)) + geom_point()

#improving by geom_jitter()
ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = cty, y = hwy)) + geom_jitter()

#improving by geom_count()
ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = cty, y = hwy)) + geom_count()

#improving by alpha
ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = cty, y = hwy)) + geom_point(alpha=0.25)

  1. width controls the amount of vertical displacement and height controls the amount of horizontal displacement.

  2. geom_jitter() handles overplotting by adding a small amount of random variation to the location of each point. The disadvantages of geom_jitter are that it changes the value of variables and that it will be less useful when the dataset is huge.
    geom_counter() handles overplotting by counting the number of observations at each location and mapping the count to point area. The disadvantage of it is that if the size of some data points is large enough, it will creates new overplotting.

  3. By default, multiple bars occupying the same x position will be stacked atop one another by position_stack(). We can use position_dodge() or position_dodge2() or position_fill() to change the default behavior.

1.4 grammar of graphics: Coordinate systems

  1. When using coord_flip(), the graph displays x conditional on y rather than displaying y conditional on x.
ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = cty, y = hwy)) + geom_point()+coord_flip()

  1. The plot below demonstrates that the city and highway miles in mpg dataset are positively related.
    geom_abline() add reference lines to a plot.
    coord_fixed() is important because it forces a specified ratio between the physical representation of data units on the axes so the ratio will remain the same when resizing the graph.
ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = cty, y = hwy)) + geom_point() + geom_abline() + coord_fixed()
